 - Background on what's going on
   - Society is drowning in slop, ethics and competence are becoming liabilities, and each day the light of humanity seems to dim a bit more
   - I can only really speak about the systems I know something about, but there are many others that are just as or more important (e.g. agriculture, healthcare etc.) that I won't be talking about today but there are many more competent folks in the group
@@ -19,7 +19,9 @@   - Examples are the EU hosting their own sovereign social media (Mastodon, on the fediverse), the Netherlands adopting their own sovereign software forge (Forgejo, also on the fediverse), the French government and more and more German states switching to Linux for public institutions, and the German government making the open ODT format instead of the proprietary Word docx format mandatory, and most EU countries now using the sovereign, federated, encrypted Matrix protocol for all communication and LibreOffice for all documents, esp. in the military
   - Democracies everywhere on the planet are fighting to remove US influence and kill switches on digital spaces from civic society in a way that has never been as present as this before
   - Usually this focuses on formats and servers, which is good, but for technology to be more resilient I think we need to go one step further and focus on our personal computing tools - phones, tablets, laptops, TVs, routers, printers, etc. - too
 - Groups that are fighting back and how
-  - Many organizations are working on fighting back on this, esp. for personal computing devices, but the most interesting one in my opinion is the Modal Collective
+  - Many organizations are working on fighting back on this, mostly via advocacy
+  - One of the most interesting one in my opinion is the Modal Collective which focuses for personal computing devices
+  - Modal helps actually build, not just advocate for, solutions to this problem
   - (I am not affiliated with the Modal Collective)
   - "Modal is a new independent collective building emancipatory software for an uncertain world"
   - "We are working towards a secure free software operating system accessible to everyone, with a solid ecosystem of apps that support multi-device sync and collaboration"
@@ -86,9 +88,22 @@   - IDE setup
   - Maintenance and GNOME Circle
   - The GNOME foundation
 - Making your local-first apps collaborative with p2panda
-  - Go over our p2panda Go bindings demos and walk through each component in the bindings step by step
-  - CRDTs and Loro CRDT in particular
-  - p2panda itself is working on many other parts of the local-first ecosystem as well (see https://p2panda.org/#libraries)
+  - Extends the stack with building blocks for P2P local-first applications
+  - Example at https://codeberg.org/pojntfx/p2panda-gobject-go/src/branch/main/examples/p2pandaapp-cli-gomod/cmd/p2pandaapp-cli-gomod-chat/main.go
+  - The core of it is a p2panda node
+  - Has a network ID, private and public key
+  - Can store persistent data either in memory or on disk
+  - Discovers nodes in your network via mDNS, but can also be pointed at a relay & another "bootstrap node" so that you can connect across networks
+  - Also supports other networks in theory (IP, Bluetooth, NAN, Mesh, sneakernet (USB sticks etc.))
+  - Within a network, the node can then create more topics by ID
+  - Any other node can then join the same network and topic securely with a share code (as we saw in Reflection)
+  - Within a topic, you can send and receive both persistent messages (which get stored in disk/memory - this is where you put long-lived data) and ephemeral messages (which don't get stored anywhere - this is where you put e.g. notifications)
+  - Based on those primitives you can build applications of almost arbitary complexity, all without a server and without having to handle all of the complexities that usually come with p2p software
+  - p2panda itself is working on many other parts of the local-first ecosystem as well, e.g. a system-level sync daemon accessible via an XDG portal, re-usable GTK widgets for things like the list of users, authentication, sending large files and more (see https://p2panda.org/#libraries)
+  - Lots of interest on this with monthly meetups and plans to integrate this deeply into every GNOME app
+  - Syncing calendar events, contacts, settings, documents, notifications, clipboard, chat - so many things are possible
+  - A lot of UX research is still to be done
+  - For resolving conflicts, CRDTs and existing local-first tooling can be super useful but is out of scope for today, for example Loro CRDT is used for Reflection
 - The hardware stack (RISC-V)
   - Software runs on hardware
   - Free Software has been around for a long time, but from the very beginning the CPUs it ran have been non-free
@@ -121,4 +136,10 @@   - Also super useful for private persons, e.g. for backing up all the data in that "important" folder with all of your passwords, 2FA recovery codes, SIN numbers, copies of passports and tax information etc.
   - Still in early days, still brainstorming this together with a librarian friend who knows much more about the analog part of this than me
 - Workshop: Crafting Inkling, a p2panda-powered GNOME app to share ideas with others during the talk
